  "datePublished": "2026-01-01",
  "description": "Recursion is a technique in which a function solves a problem by calling itself with a simpler version of the same problem. Each recursive call reduces the problem until it reaches a base case — a version simple enough to solve directly without further recursion.\nA classic example is computing the factorial of a number. The factorial of 5 (written 5!) is 5 times 4 times 3 times 2 times 1. A recursive definition captures this: the factorial of n is n multiplied by the factorial of (n - 1), and the factorial of 1 is 1. The function calls itself repeatedly, each time with a smaller number, until it reaches 1 and begins returning results back up the chain of calls.\n",
